{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.21,0.37,0.11,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7888"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82306"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7682"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34245"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory technician is examining urinary sediment under light microscopy to identify crystal morphology in a patient with nephrolithiasis. One particular type of kidney stone characteristically appears as rectangular prisms or hexagonal plates with a \u0027coffin lid\u0027 appearance under microscopic examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of kidney stones would most likely display this microscopic appearance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uric acid","Struvite","Calcium oxalate","Calcium phosphate","Cystine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStruvite\u003C/strong\u003E stones (magnesium ammonium phosphate) characteristically appear as rectangular \u0027coffin lid\u0027 or prismatic crystals with three to six sides under microscopic examination. This distinctive morphology is a key diagnostic feature of struvite stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other types of kidney stones have different microscopic appearances:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUric acid\u003C/strong\u003E stones typically appear as pleomorphic crystals that may be rhomboid, rosette-shaped, or needle-like. They are often yellow-brown in color and have smooth surfaces.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium oxalate\u003C/strong\u003E stones can appear as envelope-shaped or octahedral (dihydrate) or dumbbell-shaped (monohydrate) crystals. The dihydrate form resembles tiny envelopes under microscopy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E stones typically form wedge-shaped, prism-like, or rosette crystals. They are often white and chalky in appearance.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystine\u003C/strong\u003E stones appear as hexagonal, flat, benzene-ring shaped crystals. While cystine crystals are also hexagonal like struvite, they are distinctly flatter and more plate-like without the three-dimensional \u0027coffin lid\u0027 appearance. Cystine crystals often have more uniform hexagonal shapes compared to the more variable prismatic appearance of struvite.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe identification of struvite crystals in urinary sediment is diagnostically significant as it indicates the presence of urinary tract infection with urease-producing bacteria such as Proteus, Klebsiella, or Pseudomonas species. These bacteria split urea into ammonia, creating an alkaline urinary environment that promotes struvite stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Struvite stones appear as hexagonal or rectangular prisms microscopically, often described as \u0027coffin lid\u0027 shaped crystals.","Crystal morphology is a key diagnostic feature in identifying different types of kidney stones under microscopy.","Struvite stones form due to urinary tract infections with urease-producing bacteria."],"references":["Khan SR, Pearle MS, Robertson WG, Gambaro G, Canales BK, Doizi S, Traxer O, Tiselius HG. Kidney stones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Feb 25;2:16008. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.8. PMID: 27188687; PMCID: PMC5685519.","Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Murphy PB. Renal Calculi, Nephrolithiasis. [Updated 2024 Apr 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442014/","stroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences. \t\tFontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82306"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82306"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T08:31:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T08:32:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7888"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4946"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Histology and Cytology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T10:20:36+10:30"},"relationships